 This install applies to "Overdrive" © 1993 Team 17

 This install requires WHDLoad and RawDIC to be in the path. Both can be found
 in the WHDLoad package.
 To install from a different drive than DF0: select installation mode Expert.

 The installed program requires 0.5 MB ChipMem and 1.5 MB OtherMem.
 It can be quit by pressing num '*' (key can be changed with Tooltype "QuitKey=").

 If you have problems with this installation please try and get a newer
 version of this package from the WHDLoad WWW-Page. If that doesn't help try
 some Tooltypes like NOCACHE, NOAUTOVEC, NOVBRMOVE, NOMMU, PAL or NTSC. If
 that also fails, please inform the author via the Bug-Report-Form which
 can be accessed on the WHDLoad WWW-Page or create a mantis issue directly
 at http://mantis.whdload.de

 For the full WHDLoad package, other installs and updates refer to:
	http://www.whdload.de/
 or	aminet:dev/misc/whdload#?
 and	aminet:game/patch/

 version 2.1 (05.06.2026) done by Arise from decay & JOTD
 - only needs 512k of chipmem instead of 1MB
 - comprehensive trainer added by Arise from decay
 
 version 2.0 (25.05.2004) done by JOTD
 - rewritten slave completely for WHDLoad
 - fixed load/save records (old record files are no longer valid!)

 version 1.4 (01.11.2002) done by JOTD
 - rewritten install script for WHDLoad
 - new imager, from Codetapper PDOS imagers
 - shorter slave (does not include boot data anymore)
 - documentation included
 - source code included
 - warning: old images are not compatible (and were trashed anyway)

 version 1.x (??.??.1997) done by JOTD:
 - Save/Load records on hard drive
 - Decrunch routines relocated in fast memory
 - Full use of fast memory
 - Fixed an annoying white->black fade when accessing a disk (loss of time, aggressive).

note from JOTD:

At least: now only needs 512k of chipmem (fixed stupid decrunch bug
by moving expansion memory by 16 bytes!). I can't believe that I left that issue
so long in this slave. Thanks to Arise from decay for updating it for trainer,
inadvertantly enabling fastmem (but without MMU on his system), which made me wonder
why it didn't work anymore for a long time (until he told me he changed it!).
Then I fixed it by just adding a few bytes, at start so decrunch won't read out
of bounds, and the game is probably even smoother and loads faster.

This game is super hard and well deserves a good trainer!
   
   